---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Technical Brief: Sovereign Public Information | OpenPublicInfo.ie">
  <main class="py-20">
    <article class="container-tight prose prose-slate max-w-none">
      <header class="mb-16 border-b-4 border-brand-text pb-8">
        <span class="text-brand-accent font-black uppercase tracking-widest text-sm mb-4 block">Official Briefing Document</span>
        <h1 class="text-5xl md:text-6xl font-black uppercase leading-none mb-6">
          Sovereign Public<br/> Information Standards
        </h1>
        <div class="flex flex-col md:flex-row gap-8 text-sm uppercase font-bold text-slate-500">
          <div><span class="text-slate-400">To:</span> Irish Public Bodies & Regulatory Authorities</div>
          <div><span class="text-slate-400">Date:</span> May 2026</div>
          <div><span class="text-slate-400">Ref:</span> OPI-2026-001</div>
        </div>
      </header>

      <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-black uppercase mb-6">Executive Summary</h2>
        <p class="text-xl leading-relaxed">
          Current communication practices among Irish public bodies—including transport providers, local authorities, and emergency services—frequently treat private, account-gated social media platforms as primary notification hubs. This creates a <strong>Two-Tier Information System</strong> that excludes citizens based on platform membership.
        </p>
        <p class="text-xl leading-relaxed">
          This brief proposes a <strong>"Source First"</strong> notification standard. It advocates for a <strong>decentralized architecture</strong> where each public body maintains its own digital sovereignty by publishing data to its own domain in a standardized, machine-readable format.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-black uppercase mb-6">1. The Problem: The "Gatekeeper" Model</h2>
        <p>
          Whether it is a train delay, a water main burst, or a public health alert, vital information is increasingly "walled off" within private ecosystems.
        </p>
        <ul class="space-y-4">
          <li><strong>Gated Access:</strong> Citizens are often practically coerced into creating third-party accounts just to receive real-time updates from state-funded bodies.</li>
          <li><strong>Data Dependency:</strong> Public bodies have become dependent on the algorithms and uptime of private, foreign-owned corporations for essential public communication.</li>
          <li><strong>Accessibility Failure:</strong> Social-media-first publishing fails to meet statutory accessibility obligations, as these platforms are outside the control and auditing of the state.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="mb-16 bg-slate-100 p-8 border-l-8 border-brand-text">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-black uppercase mb-6 italic text-brand-accent">2. The "Source First" Architecture</h2>
        <p class="text-lg mb-6">
          We propose a <strong>Federated Publication Model</strong>. Instead of a central hub, each body owns its own data and publishes it to its own infrastructure first.
        </p>
        <div class="bg-white p-6 shadow-md border-t-4 border-brand-accent mb-8">
          <h3 class="font-bold uppercase text-xs mb-2 text-brand-accent tracking-widest text-brand-text">The Sovereign Publication Workflow</h3>
          <p class="text-sm text-brand-text font-mono font-bold leading-relaxed">
            [Public Body Incident] &rarr; [Internal CMS] &rarr; [Official Website / API] &rarr; [Automated Social Media Mirror]
          </p>
          <p class="text-xs text-green-700 mt-4 font-bold text-brand-text">Benefit: The official website remains the Single Source of Truth (SSOT).</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-black uppercase mb-6">3. Technical Requirements</h2>
        
        <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4 uppercase tracking-tight text-slate-700">3.1 Edge Ownership of Data</h3>
        <p class="mb-6">
          Each public body (e.g., Irish Rail, Dublin City Council, HSE) must be responsible for the "edge" publication of their own alerts. By publishing to their own domain (e.g., <code>council.ie/alerts</code>), they ensure that the data remains accessible even if third-party social networks are unavailable or restricted.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4 uppercase tracking-tight text-slate-700">3.2 Universal Standards for Aggregation</h3>
        <p class="mb-6">
          While publication is decentralized, <strong>data formats must be standardized</strong>. This allows regulatory bodies (like the NTA or Department of Health) and independent developers to aggregate alerts into unified dashboards without manual intervention.
        </p>
        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-8">
          <div class="border-t border-slate-200 pt-4">
            <h4 class="font-bold text-brand-text uppercase text-sm mb-2 italic tracking-widest text-brand-accent underline underline-offset-4 decoration-2">Standardized JSON/RSS</h4>
            <p class="text-sm">A baseline requirement for all bodies. Every alert must be available as a machine-readable entry on the official domain, allowing for simple scraping or polling by news outlets and community groups.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="border-t border-slate-200 pt-4">
            <h4 class="font-bold text-brand-text uppercase text-sm mb-2 italic tracking-widest text-brand-accent underline underline-offset-4 decoration-2 text-brand-accent">GTFS-Realtime (Transit)</h4>
            <p class="text-sm">Specific to the transport sector. The <code>ServiceAlerts</code> feed must be used as the primary broadcast method, ensuring that third-party maps and official apps stay in sync with the source.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="mb-16 border-t-4 border-slate-200 pt-12">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-black uppercase mb-6">Recommendations</h2>
        <ol class="space-y-6">
          <li class="pl-4">
            <strong>Enforce SSOT Policy:</strong> Mandate that all state-funded bodies publish real-time alerts to their own domain as a prerequisite for funding.
          </li>
          <li class="pl-4">
            <strong>Implement Automated Mirroring:</strong> Replace manual social media posting with automated "push-from-web" workflows to ensure data parity.
          </li>
          <li class="pl-4">
            <strong>Open Data Mandate:</strong> Require that all public safety, transport, and utility alerts be published in open, non-proprietary formats (RSS, JSON, GTFS-R).
          </li>
        </ol>
      </section>

      <footer class="mt-24 pt-12 border-t border-slate-200 text-slate-500 italic text-sm">
        <p>This document was drafted by the OpenPublicInfo.ie initiative. For technical consultation or further briefing, contact <a href="mailto:munim2020@gmail.com" class="text-brand-accent underline">Munim Kazia</a>.</p>
      </footer>
    </article>
  </main>
</Layout>
